text:
part 2
a few things about me that aren't always visible on the surface :
- i am an absolute moon lover and i always dreamt of having my own house one day where i have a huge sky light to watch the moon and stars at night.
- nature is my safe haven. i can retreat to it for weeks with no cell phone, laptop or any other electronics and be content.
- you won't see me cry often, i just don't like doing that. especially in front of people.
- but surround me with gem stones, rocks and geode's...you might see my teary eyes as i keep saying over and over subhanallah, subhanallah, subhanallah... allah swt is so great!
- as a kid i loved climbing trees! these days when i see a tree i have to fight my urge to climb one. i am not as flexible like i used to be anymore lol.
- i was sexually assaulted and i still fight with that traumatic experience. important movements such as #timesup and #metoo often trigger the flashbacks. some days are tougher than others.
- i have attempted suicide multiple times. but my angel, emine kÃ¼bra, was always the reason that i knocked sense back into myself. honestly, i wanted to live so desperately, but i didn't know anymore how.
- i seem super awkward and quiet. but honestly, i'm just selective to whom i show my true colours. because i'm a fucking delight to be around! - my talent is reading people. sometimes. when i look someone in the eye i can see the life they had before meeting me.
- i shaved off all of my hair once, at least once a day i think about doing it again :)
- i self reflect a lot, you might think : "this girl shares too much of her life and processes on the internet!" but in reality...that barely covers a 10% of what's going on in my head!

text:
when i see you again......
i know you watch over us. i know you are at peace. i still reach for my phone to call you. the pain eases but it never goes away. 
i wish i could tell you one more time how important you were to all of us. 
i wish i could have been there for you at your darkest moments. 
i wish you had not felt the only way out of your pain was to end your life. 
i wish you knew how much you were loved. 
anthony... you may be gone but not forgotten. years since that tragic day has passed but you are still part of our story, our life and our heart. 
until i see you again. â¤ï¸ #suicidesucks

text:
long before the â€œbreak-upâ€ that fueled my fire... -
-
-
i was a student in college, who had grown tired of sports. i was a gymnast since age 5. i competed in gymnastics, basketball, track and softball until the age of 18. -
-
needless to say, when i got to college, i just wanted to â€œhave fun.â€ i received offers to move forward at the collegiate level but turned them down. -
-
i worked, studied, partied and dated, which was consuming in itself. until one night, my party mentality backfired. i was taken advantage of. yes, #metoo - -
this ultimately was devastating at first. i honestly didnâ€™t know what to think of myself or the situation. i didnâ€™t even tell my family in fear they would think i was crazy. after all, i lived in south dakota. that stuff just â€œdoesnâ€™t happen.â€ -
-
i began eating my feelings until one afternoon i found myself in the drive thru at culverâ€™s, just balling my eyes out. â€œwhat am i doing?â€-
-
i began running long distance and striving to find the girl i once was. iâ€™m not sure if i was running from the pain, but nonetheless i wanted to change and beat this thing that was breaking me. i felt and believed i wasnâ€™t good enough.
-
i then moved to florida for a change. i began meeting great people at my new job. i ran two half marathons, tore my meniscus and met that someone who fueled my now bodybuilding fire. he cheated and here we are... -
-
so you see, you will be okay. every obstacle prepares you for your next chapter. itâ€™s up to you to notice when the universe is guiding you into your best self. keep moving forward!
-

text: ..i was basically tortured. my mother only got mad at my brother for a while & then he apologized and so and she forgave him, she is still silent about it, trying to block it from her mind or something & never spoke about it since. i was silenced about it too, muted sometimes by money/a car/materialistic things or such when i snapped at her once or twice unfortunately. i was blamed a little and shamed at that time for not speaking or maybe going to him sometimes even though i was a child/teen & i got used to it. i try to avoid him as much now & i kinda trying to be away from my family since october 2017 but i went back to renew my expired passport & basically suffered the trauma all over again. i'm extending stays here in the us till i find something that keeps me here. i don't want anything to do with them but they are still there attached to me & i'm kinda trapped by them by a lot of things.. sometimes i hate myself, sex, i go "a" sexual, & i'm only attracted to boys. i got abused by them too & i didn't do anything maybe i was enjoying it from what i got through & used to from my family. sometimes i hate everything & want to just end it, stop my mind, my thinking. i thought of suicide.. but i think my strong, surviving, ambitious, hopefull, brave soul is never giving up though. i didn't speak guys to be sympathized or feeling sorry for..no, mostly because i want to heal while the world know that about me. it helps a lot & i hope you feel me just a little".. thank you for reading this and sorry if it is sad or tragic but it is basically one of the major things that has a deep affect on me and my life and i'm still suffering from it. thank you rose @rosemcgowan for inspiring and encouraging me to share this, i love you endlessly sister.. ğŸ’—ğŸ’ªğŸ» #sexualassult #sexualabuse #molestation #survivor #brave #strong #rosearmy #metoo #lgbt #humanrights

"i pledge to make women safe in a world full of men"...tag every man you know who will take this pledge!!!!! when we designed the #protectourgirls by any means necessary tee we also designed another tee.  we didnt release that tee because we were unsure of the words we wanted to say, just that we were certain we wanted men to hold other men accountable in order to affect the change this culture is in desperate need of.  we want to change the narrative of "a girl child ain't safe in a world full of men!" so we waited, and the message came to us via @mrhypeup
*
* â€œwomen have been held responsible for the actions of irresponsible, inconsiderate, over-indulgent, entitled, sexually hyperactive men for far too long. itâ€™s time we held men accountable for their behaviour and insist on appropriate autonomy over their thoughts, emotions and actions.
*
we must challenge society to disrupt the patriarchal ideologies that maintain the understanding that create opportunities for men to pursue immediate sexual gratification by any means necessary." thanks to @mrhypeup for the post.

text:
on day 10 of black history month, we're celebrating buffalo native beverly johnson, the groundbreaking supermodel who helped fuel the #metoo movement.

johnson, among others, helped create a national avalanche of attention to sexual assault when she publicly shared her own allegations of being drugged at home of entertainment mogul bill cosby via a cup of cappuccino. but before her pivotal first-person piece in vanity fair in 2014, and before she became the first black model to make it to the cover of vogue in the u.s. and elle in france, johnson was a star swimmer in the queen city. in fact, she almost made it to the olympics. 
johnson attended buffalo's bennett high school, the same school as late entertainer rick james, and excelled at sports, winning a number of swimming championships. she came close to making the u.s. national team in the 100-yard freestyle for the 1968 olympics in mexico city.

after graduation, johnson went on to northeastern university in boston on a full scholarship with the intent of becoming a lawyer, but friends convinced her to try modeling. in the 1970s, she moved to new york city to try her luck. one day, she walked into the offices of glamour magazine and they hired her on the spot for a photo shoot. by the mid 1970s, johnson was in heavy demand. she appeared on the cover of the u.s. version of vogue in august 1974 and the french edition of elle a year later. 
in december of 2014, vanity fair published a first-person piece by johnson describing how cosby, she wrote, served her cappuccino laced with drugs during a visit at his home in the 1980s to audition for a role on the cosby show. she recognized what was happening, even in her drugged state, and verbally attacked  him, she wrote, prompting cosby to wordlessly pull her outside and shove her into a taxi.

wrote johnson in vanity fair: "i had to use my voice as a sister, mother and grandmother, and as a woman who knows that, according to the cdc, nearly one in five women has been sexually assaulted at some time in her life, that women of color face an even higher attack rate." #blackhistorymonth2019 #buffaloblackhistory (photos courtesy grosvenor room genealogy; alchetron)
name: Beyond the Railroad

text:
footage of nigel farage swigging a pint and thanking steve bannon and breitbart for the brexit result was deleted from a breitbart youtube channel, following the data scandal surrounding cambridge analytica.
.
- well done bannon, well done breitbart, the ex-ukip leader announces in the short clip. - you helped with this. hugely.

farageâ€™s nod to steve bannon certainly hasnâ€™t aged well in the context of the recent storm around cambridge analyticaâ€™s influence over the eu referendum.

it was revealed that data from 50 million facebook profiles were looked at against the electoral register, and then used to build an algorithm which analyses peopleâ€™s personality traits in relation to their voting behaviour.

this data could then be used to find potential swing voters and create messages tailored to influence them politically.

the firmâ€™s vice president at the time was steve bannon, who was also head of the right-wing website breitbart and was running donald trumpâ€™s campaign to become us president.

anna o'donohue

text:
ajay devgn on #metoo in bollywood: canâ€™t be judgemental until somebody is proven guilty
#
ajay devgn, who has supported the #metoo movement in the past, believes the power game does not work anymore in the industry. (photo: varinder chawla) ajay devgn says he was shocked by the #metoo allegations against some of the prominent names in the indian film industry but he believes a due course of law should be followed in such cases. several bollywood personalities such as directors rajkumar hirani, subhash ghai, sajid khan, vikas bahl and rajat kapoor, actor alok nath, singer kailash kher and music composer anu malik were called out for sexually harassing women over the years. â€œa couple of things came out and some people are like this but everybody is not like that. i would say some names did shock me but then i canâ€™t be judgmental completely till somebody proves someone guilty or not,â€ ajay told pti. ajay, who has supported the movement in the past, believes the power game does not work anymore in the industry. â€œnew generation is thinking differently, they are not going to accept the bullshit what people used to accept couple of years back. they are changing and we are changing and that change is for better. with the media comingâ€¦

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
i used to think anger was a bad, unhealthy, mean emotion. like if i felt anger towards anyone, it was always accompanied by a texas-sized portion of guilt on the side. but iâ€™m beginning to see anger as a necessary counterpart to real self-love.
â€¢
kristen neff, an associate professor in human development and culture at my alma mater @utaustintx , has made self-compassion her lifeâ€™s work. whenever i think about self-compassion, my head goes to that kind, tender love i give myself when i fail or do something wrong. â€œitâ€™s ok, ellenâ€¦youâ€™re still a badass even though you didnâ€™t win that account.â€ thatâ€™s what neff describes as â€œyin self-compassion.â€ but thereâ€™s are times when itâ€™s 100% appropriate to have a fierce, tough self-compassion in order to protect yourself and create the change that is necessary in the world. and this is when i believe your anger becomes a strong, valuable asset. â€¢
we see this most evidently in the #metoo movement as brave women have used their voices in powerful ways to call the men that wronged them to accountability for their actions. but it also exists in the nooks and crannies of mundane work life. iâ€™ve been in countless situations where my voice and perspective were not being respected or were just plain ignored, primarily because of my gender and iâ€™m sure because iâ€™m a poc. but it wasnâ€™t until fairly recently that i started loudly and unapologetically calling this behavior out, shining a thousand-watt light on it, and demanded change. this was me exercising full yang self-compassion, protecting myself and wanting to create change for other women i worked with who fell victim to the same type of treatment.
â€¢
so as we have been exploring #selflove leading up to #valentinesday , i offer up this for you to consider: how can you use your anger to practice fierce self-love and compassion? how can you use your anger to create real change? may we all be more conscious of practicing both our yin and our yang self-compassion. #wearealldaughters

text:
today in black history we honor the silence 
we the silent screams of our foremothers
the screams swallowed 
while we were raped 
the screams tucked into the darkest places 
of our souls 
so as not to wake the children 
and see more horror in their eyes 
so as not to wake the men 
and see the pain of not being able to protect us 
the emasculation of being powerless 
when master rapes your wife 
we the sobs hushed 
we the refrains muffled 
we the words that didnâ€™t part from our teeth 
because 
we did best to know our place 
we did best not to be uppity 
or think that we may deserve dignity 
we that learned a down cast eye 
kept us alive 
we the tears flowing like waterfalls 
perpetually inside 
while our sons swung 
high 
and died 
our feet bleed beneath our skin 
our backs shredded within 
our lips closed and tight 
our tongue tattooed with perpetual bite 
we learned to suffer in silence to save ourselves
to save our men and children 
we learned too well 
we the tired 
we the weary
we the screams
we the sirens
we are silent no more 
you will hear us 
our feet marching 
with the screams of our ancestors at our backs 
like wind in our sails 
vengeance that has laid waiting for too long 
we will open our mouths 
and you will never hear the same again 
our screams will echo in your souls forever 
our #metoo began before hollywood 
before trump grabbed pussies 
stand with your alabaster tears 
for as long as you can 
but move when you hear my army 
move when you hear my battle cry 
move when you feel the presence of my lineage 
silent no more 
#fistandfire #silentnomore  #weareourancestorswildestdreams #youwillhearus #buymybookplease

smooth jazz chicago is a collection of various jazz artist originated from all over the us brought together to provide some most fantastic acts seen in the chicagoland area. according to their website they encourage talent of all kinds in the musical genre by not having a application process for performing artists for their events.Â  they are only able to book established nationally-known artists represented by national booking agencies. 
artists must have a strong history of being able attract 600 or more paying customers (per show) toÂ  contemporary jazz shows in the chicago area - in which they were the primary headliner.Â  although, they discourage the submission of unsolicited artist/musician media kits. such material is generally discarded upon receipt. you can follow them at www.smoothchicago.com or by text your name & email address to
(312) 725-0740.

text:
the government has launched a consultation into the 3 month time limit to raise a tribunal claim for pregnant women and new mums - we need your help.

this is our chance to shout as loud as we can that women need greater access to justice. the idea that pregnant women and new mums can start a tribunal process within 3 months is utter insanity and it results in 0.6% of victims raising a claim. i was sacked when i was 4 months pregnant and a week later i discovered i was having a high risk pregnancy. the doctor said to me: 'whatever you do, dont get stressed.' the 3 month time limit forced me to choose between the health of my baby and accessing the justice i deserved.

i need you all to send an email to the people at beis so they know how important this is. the more emails they get, the more likely it is they will do something about this. i have even written the email for you so all you have to do is copy and paste. the link is in my bio. please comment below to say you have done it so we have an idea how many emails they get.

if you want to help ignite change, then now is your chance. 
big thanks to @olga.fitzroy for her help with this.
#givemesix #pregnantthenscrewed #metoo #timesup
name: Joeli Brearley

text:
the stages of life are similar to a rose meaning that we have to nourish our minds, body, and souls in order for us to grow into the person god intended us to be.  like a rose our lives our suppose to represent 3 things

1. promise - having faith in god to see you through the storms or seasons of growth.

2. hope - trusting god to reveal your purpose and  showing you the way to live a fulfilling life.

text:
dear friends... in addition to all the beautiful photos of clothes, children and their cool parents that we love to share, today i would like to talk about something that is very close to my heart and has become more and more of a concern in recent times. the current debate on sexism has been going on for a relatively long time since the #metoo movement and, with the last women's march in every major city, shows how much change and development is needed. there will be important and necessary discussions that will finally find an open ear of the wider public, but will take years to resolve the injustices mentioned - or, unfortunately, not.
because when i look around in our kindergarten (for your information a completely average kindergarten in downtown hamburg), i notice the following: girls are wearing pink, purple, sometimes red or orange. they dress up as princesses or fairies on carnival and all love elsa, the ice princess. the boys wear dark blue, dark green and in crazy cases sometimes red. fire engine red of course. featured are bob the builder, ninjago and robbers. there are in my eyes two main explanations. on the one hand, it is alleged: "no, he / she doesnâ€™t have that from me, she / he likes it all by himself or from the other children." on the other hand people could sometimes say: "there is no other choice.". both explanations are of course wrong, but i can understand, when parents try to find excuses and donâ€™t want to search for gender-neutral clothes in the evening. it's like being at war with children. everyone just tries to survive somehow ... itâ€™s clear, however, that the primary caregiver affects their children the most, no matter how long they are cared for differently during the day. even those who do not actively tell their children about gender roles influence their behavior by their own and for me, that includes accepting prevailing conditions in the form of clothes that suggests certain gender roles. there's nothing wrong with girls wearing clothes and guys playing with excavators, but we should let them choose for themselves and not subconsciously force them into one direction... have a look into our stories to read more!âœŒğŸ¼

text:
in business and even friendships, i used to feel that if i said no when people ask things from me i would hurt their feelings or make them angry.

if i said no they would call me a b#$ch for not supporting. 
if i said no then i could never ask them for help in the future. 
people can drain your energy trying to reach their own personal goals and kick you to the side when they don't need you anymore. 
two letters. one word can set you free.

because in the end you are the most important person in this scenario. "no" can give you freedom but on my terms. have you ever felt the same? 
#notofreedom #supermamalebanon

text:
as an intersectional feminist, a biology major with the end goal of working in human healthcare, a survivor of sexual assault and abuse, someone who has struggled with their body image and self-esteem for a very long time (largely due to misogyny/misogynoir and having my body hyper-sexualized in a variety of ways growing up), and especially someone with a vagina, i think the ways in which we have conversations about vaginas matter. itâ€™s still very taboo, despite the fact that vaginas play a very relevant role in our daily lives, from sex to child-bearing to menstruation. i admittedly didnâ€™t know much about vagina monologues when i auditioned, doing so mainly because wac encouraged me, but after doing my research and being involved in this production, i see that my thoughts and experiences are not isolated ones. we should not be ashamed of our bodies and genitalia, and the ways in which they intertwine with our identities, sexuality, and health. i think this is an important play to start the much needed conversations we should be having. not only in this #metoo era, but also in an age where we are more aware of its exclusive natures, and how we are able to make said conversations change with the way our perceptions of gender, sexuality, sexual orientation, sex itself, race and culture, class, misogyny, feminism, and intersectionality are all changing.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
sunday gratitude. i woke up with a positive attitude and grateful heart, i wanted to share.
 i am grateful to rise again on a brand new day, to live again, to have the opportunity to choose my path. 
i am thankful for my support system, those who love me and don't give up on me when times have been tough. thank you for giving me grace but also knowing when to call me on my shit. 
i rejoice in my talents, gifts, abilities and skills. i know by honing these and listening to my gut i will continue to grow through my trauma.
what are you grateful for? i'd love to hear!

on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,Â wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrestedÂ earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,Â wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrestedÂ earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
fire rose survivor tattooğŸŒ¹ğŸ”¥ ; which represents strength & unity. this tattoo is a testament for the community of sexual assault survivors.

i am a very private person as many know, but i felt the need to share this. 
i told myself i would never get another tattoo again, but this time is so different. this has so much meaning to me. i needed something tangible, something that i can use as a reminder. not of my assault, but of my strength and courage. i still struggle with blaming myself, ptsd & etc. but today i reclaimed my body. i am finally on the path of healing. it will take a long time but i am finally ready. this happens to so many woman every year, every month, every day. donâ€™t let your voice go unheard. your story is important. you are important. and most of all, you are not alone. 
iâ€™m not a victim, iâ€™m a survivor.

text: this novel explores the complexities of the modern feminist movement - following greer as she starts college and is finding her way in the world. the discussions of being away from home for the first time, #metoo situations, making new friends and deciding on a career path took me nostalgically (and sometimes painfully) back to my own college days. i felt a deep connection to greer in those early pages. as the novel continued, the story lost its thrill for me a bit, meandering slowly thru the characters lives, but i really appreciated the deep character development - making me committed to seeing the book through. even though this story didnâ€™t fully grip me emotionally all the way through, iâ€™m interested enough in wolitzerâ€™s writing style to pursue some of her previous novels. not a deep read for womenâ€™s issues, but anything that gets us contemplating these ideas is good right? 7.5/10 would recommend

text:
i've heard/read that there is a belief circling that neichze's philosophy aligned with that of the nazi's. after a fair degree of vetting, this seems to absolutely not be true. 
his writings were taken, vastly manipulated by others for their own gain, then further by hitler.

he would have found their ideology beyond abhorrent. 
also possibly of interest is that he spent the last 10 years of his life in mental wards, due to the neurological effects of syphilis, they believed. 
but his last act, with sound mind, was to aggressively confront a man that was brutally abusing a horse in the street. fredrick locks eyes with the horse and says "i feel you, brother. i feel your pain." and then he checked out, for ever.

at least that's how the story goes.. #itsjusttoomuch

text: diy punk. inclusive, more than an image and presentation. where i'm from; bars are for old people. 3 friends can rent a house affordably, skate down banisters. throw a party so out of shapperones often moving afterwards is necessary. accountability,  responsibility and cleaning is part of the jam itself, adulting. it's a way of lifestyle and attitude more than a party, presentation and scene. no one cares if i'm smelly they're all greasy too. no stage just jumping off counter tops. removing plants is ideal, spill earth everywhere. inside fun. punk used to mean something. challenging the man, protests, at home it's not at all about drugs or drinking, i don't understand it here. very capitalist supporting scene kids running around, having the priveledge to gossip from the valley, if someone goes to better themselves and get a community supporting job they're a sell out. i see a sellout as anyone in any place fucking for promotions. so most of you. sure some people sell out to work on things, but it's sad you talk about your parents the ones who still fund you like that. and any professional at all, who's trying to get out of that background. so you high horse and take money from those who are still supporting your failure to thrive. anyone ever helping you, you call that, as you drink, drug, fuck, cry like pansy. while supporting capitalism and not helping anyone else lazily. not even productive efficient lazily, just offensive in lack of personhood. diy punks for the win, bringing back raising questions and awareness, more than an image of being misunderstood, in a stance of you will damn hear and attempt to understand. #freepress #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #inclusive #diypunks

=============================
julie has been involved in issues impacting women and girls since the 1970â€™s when she was in college at george washington university and co-founded and led my sisterâ€™s place, the first comprehensive shelter, hotline, education and advocacy program serving women and children living in violent homes in washington dc. jones was instrumental in organizing the first national meeting on domestic violence at the white house in 1977 and the first hearings on domestic violence by the us commission on civil rights (usccr) in 1978. todayâ€™s national coalition on domestic violence was formed by grassroots participants at the usccr hearings
============================

text:
â€œwillful ignoranceâ€ #blackface #politics #northam  the admission by virginia governor ralph northam that he, along with the state's attorney general, mark herring, had dressed in blackface in the 1980s, has unearthed the recent history of the practice. many are shocked; some are not surprised. 
along with the #metoo movement, we are confronted with serious and hard-to-answer questions. is any questionable behavior in one's past cause for vilification? or is it important to see how that person has changed? is redemption possible in the public sphere? does it matter if one is in the limelight as a politician, actor, or movie mogul? do we take into account the culture of the times as we might when looking at the life of, say, thomas jefferson? his writings are a foundation for our country, yet he was a slave owner and even had a child by one of his slaves. context may be everything or not.

the revelations of these virginia legislators hit us hard and fast. not surprising in this 24/7 news cycle. the preponderance of blackface photos in college yearbooks and the exhuming of this shallowly buried racial past has only deepened our concerns. what do we do with these facts? how do we respond? 
three recent washington post op-eds give us possible paths. yes, politicians wore blackface. it used to be all-american â€˜fun.â€™ by rhae lynn barnes, assistant professor of american cultural history at princeton university, how ralph northam and others can repent of americaâ€™s original sin by reverend william j. barber ii, co-chair of the poor peopleâ€™s campaign: a national call for moral revival, and from former congresswoman donna edwards: iâ€™m from the same generation as northam and herring. their behavior is mind-boggling.

what i do know is that talking about it, looking at it, and listening to others is the only way through this. otherwise, our ignorance isn't just ignorance, it's willful ignorance.

text:
this is not really surprising. they've been doing this crime centuries ago. look it up! but this needs to be expose over and over again because these so called 'man of god' is using religion to satisfy their lust.

news bbc news navigation
sections

pope admits clerical abuse of nuns including sexual slavery

pope francis made the admission while visiting the middle east
pope francis has admitted that clerics have sexually abused nuns, and in one case they were kept as sex slaves.

he said in that case his predecessor, pope benedict, was forced to shut down an entire congregation of nuns who were being abused by priests.

it is thought to be the first time that pope francis has acknowledged the sexual abuse of nuns by the clergy.

he said the church was attempting to address the problem but said it was "still going on". last november, the catholic church's global organisation for nuns denounced the "culture of silence and secrecy" that prevented them from speaking out.

the pope's comments come amid long-running cases of sexual abuse of children and young men by priests at the church.

child sex abuse and the catholic church
profile: pope francis
what did pope francis say?
speaking to reporters while on a historic tour of the middle east on tuesday, the pontiff admitted that the church had an issue, and the roots lay in society "seeing women as second class". he said that priests and bishops had abused nuns, but said the church was aware of the "scandal" and was "working on it", adding that a number of clerics had been suspended. "it's a path that we've been on," he said. "pope benedict had the courage to dissolve a female congregation which was at a certain level, because this slavery of women had entered it - slavery, even to the point of sexual slavery - on the part of clerics or the founder." pope francis said sexual abuse of nuns was an ongoing problem, but happened largely in "certain congregations, predominantly new ones". "i think it's still taking place because it's not as though the moment you become aware of something it goes away."

text:
(swipe for full piece)
normally i post the whole thing, but i didn't want to upset anyone that's maybe been through something similar. so, i guess this is a trigger warning. 
lately i've wanted to talk more about things that are personal. and one of the ways i've been able to do that is to talk as if it's to someone else. it's a little cowardly but it's how i'm getting through. 
hey you, strong one, waking up everyday. i see you. 
let me know what you think â¤
check out my other work â¤
follow for more â¤

valentineâ€™s day is just around the corner, and i thought i would share some thoughts for the single ladies in the room. â™¥ï¸ sometimes being single sucks. there are people (mostly married people) who will tell you not to rush it and enjoy this season. those people ğŸ¤¬. â™¥ï¸ donâ€™t get me wrong, i l o v e my alone time. i am happy by myself. i am good at being alone. but i donâ€™t want to be perpetually alone. i want a partner, a friend, someone who loves me even though i can quote all seasons of gilmore girls. â™¥ï¸ i donâ€™t have any answers as to why the crazy girl has been married seven times, and i canâ€™t find one. and i think not knowing is okay. i think you can simultaneously be very happy with everything you bring to the table and still long for your person. 
so maybe this valentineâ€™s day you are alone, and you are in that season of waiting. #metoo i get it. all of it. i see you. â™¥ï¸ but, you best believe i bought myself jewelry, and i can buy my own chocolate. i do every other day of the year.

text: not the most flattering picture not the most flattering shirt ğŸ˜‚. but i had to face a lot of unflattering truths about myself & about my experiences with sexual abuse. i had to get raw & naked with myself about my truth and it has been one of the most difficult wounds iâ€™ve had to heal through. there was a moment in my healing journey that my denial just crumbled right before me. i got a huge slap on the face about my experiences, my story , my truth about sexual abuse. i got hit with the realization of how much the sexual abuse had affected my life, my reality, my relationships. [[i mean it has completely re-structured my brain. think about it getting sexually abused & doing things against your will that you donâ€™t understand at age 4 all the way through to age 12. during the most crucial years of brain development i was forced to re-structure my brain in such a way so that i could survive what i endured. it has been difficult for me to create and sustain healthy relationships among other things.]] when my denial crumbled , this was my breakthrough moment. this was the moment i needed to really begin to heal. i broke down, i cried. i was angry. i went through an emotional roller coaster. & then the real healing began. you reach a point in your healing where you realize that your experiences & the effects it has on your life wonâ€™t â€œjust go awayâ€ & you actually have to put in work! i canâ€™t tell you how many times i wanted to just stop talking about my trauma and just live a â€œnormalâ€ life uninterrupted from flashbacks, nightmares, insomnia, crying spells, eating disorders, anger episodes, etc. but i realized that in order to live uninterrupted i had to do the work it takes to heal through my trauma. quitting wasnâ€™t going to speed up my healing process. itâ€™s not easy at all. itâ€™s really hard. & itâ€™s going  to get really bad before it gets better. but itâ€™s worth it. you are worth it. itâ€™s possible to live a life uninterrupted. it will take time but when you do the work in time you will heal. you are a survivor, youâ€™ve made it through some of the worse days of your life. you can do the work to heal. iâ€™ve done it. & i continue to work to keep healing! you are not alone.

text:
the undercurrent of anger.
.
iâ€™ve been here. in fact i think i spent a solid portion of my adult life with repressed anger.
.
one day i felt safe enough to tune into that anger. it was scary. it was overwhelming and felt like a bottomless pit of rage.
.
our bodies and brains are amazing. they can create entire systems through neuro pathways of the ğŸ§ 
.
healing then becomes a process of releasing into the underlying feeling of that anger. resulting in a chemical reaction that fires different neurones in the brain creating a new pathway.
.
there is no way to true healing without the surrender to the real emotion underneath.
.
surrender. not because you give up, but because experiencing that grief will allow you to truly heal.
.
you are brave. you are a conqueror. you are safe. you are enough ğŸ’—â¤ï¸
.
.
.

text:
2020's democratic primary is looking like it's going to be a very interesting primary season. so far 10 candidates we know have jumped in that i know about. here is my stance on all of them. part one!
1. elizabeth warren 
senator from massachussetts. honestly, i don't see how she can win a general election against donald trump. she's too easy to mock, and the dna test, and the recent thing showing she identified as a native american is going to hurt her chances. at most, i can see her getting 249 electoral votes against trump. she's known to undeperform races, especially in 2018. she performed slightly worse than clinton did in 2016 in terms of margin, and the republican governor won with nearly 67% of the vote compared to her nearly 61%. she's too polarizing as well, and would be a terrible pick as the nominee. hard no on her. 
2. kirsten gillibrand
senator from new york. while just an exploratory committee, she's likely to jump in the race. she managed to weaponize #metoo and use it against her colleague al franken, who resigned, without due process. she's hated by many democrats as well because of that. i frankly don't think she'd beat trump either. i'm a hard no
3. kamala harris
senator from california. mixed bag in my opinion. before klobuchar jumped in she was my second choice, after biden. a key, but i think she has a shot  against trump. should she win the nomination, she might moderate on things like medicare for all, maybe support something more practical, like a public option. if she does that, good. 
4.  pete buttigieg (pic 6)
former mayor of south bend, indiana. would be first milennial and openly gay president if elected. he is a meh for me. 
5.  marianne williamson (pic 7)
haven't heard of her? most people don't know who she is. she works with oprah and is an author and a healer i believe. she is running on reparations for descendants of enslaved africans. pretty much no name recognition, and people say shes kind of bernie-like. reparations? sure. her? nah. 
6. andrew yang (pic 10)
an entrepreneur from north carolina, and is running on universal basic income, which frankly i don't support. he's a no for me. also, lack of name recognition

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text: today was my last day of training at rainn headquarters and i have to say that my heart is heavy as i leave. words will never be enough to share what an impact these past two days have made on my life. i feel so blessed to have been able to have the opportunity to meet so many incredible people, including other survivors. sometimes itâ€™s easy to get caught up in a world where many people are bystanders who do nothing when a crisis occurs, or filled with naysayers who donâ€™t believe itâ€™s our job to change the world. this weekend has enabled me to meet likeminded individuals who are passionate about helping others, and that alone has brought me an enormous amount of joy. i am incredibly grateful to have the chance to help others through rainn, an organization that saved me when i was in a time of crisis. iâ€™m always here for anyone who needs to talk, but rainn is an amazing resource that i encourage all survivors of sexual violence (and their loved ones) to check out. thank you to everyone who has encouraged me to follow my dreams and supported me through my struggles. none of this would have been possible without your help. #metoo #rainn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
w h i t e  w i d o w 
she carried borrowed strength down the aisle... holding back the tears and smile

her something blue was far from white.. she hid a darkness black as night

yet she walked with pride..in stride, despite...the pains she buried out of sight

a holy vision... a dream come true yet held a secret no one knew

he ripped it from her some moons before, 
she wasn't a virgin, she wasn't pure... no innocence... no new allure

he forced this womanly child to break her bloom before the time had come
too soon

she carried his seed inside her womb... buried along with rape and gloom

her grief was great... no one could see... he forced upon his bride to be

he arranged this sentence and took her dreams...the wedding bells were merely schemes

she wasn't less, yes she was more.. for all the darkness she'd endured

her blessed white rose...he crushed and tore

yet, that pure virgin soul was her's... forever more

k. davae {this poem is for my dear friend and all who have been deprived of innocence by force... you are still priceless and your strength forever to be bowed down too, they may have tried to  take your crown but never forget your still queens}ğŸ’– #igpoem #writerssociety #instagrampoetry #poetryloving #poetry_addicts #poemgasm #poetrysociety #valentines #poemsporn_ #rhapsodicwind #poemsociety #writersoninstagram #poemsforhim #poemsforher #romanticqoutes #unconditionallove #silverleafpoetry #inloveqoutes #poetryporn #tequiero #miamor #poemsporn #poetsofig #poetrycommunity #spilledwords #spilledink #sexualabuse #rape #womenwhowrite #metoo

i donâ€™t even know the person i was a year ago. fear has faded into the desire to fight. moving forward,  i know that no matter what transpires during my case, i am stronger than his actions.

text:
coming next month from @amyimpellizzeri! super excited. 
love those #tallpoppywriters "authored by a former biglaw litigator (with a career including 2 years clerking in a d.c. federal court and a decade at nycâ€™s skadden arps), impellizzeriâ€™s why we lie is a story that exposes the very core of the #metoo movement - particularly in the legal/political realm.

rising star politician and lawyer, jude birch, is clearly keeping secrets about his past from his wife, aby boyle. and aby worries that judeâ€™s relationship with his campaign manager, laila rogers, is more complicated than he has let on. jude has been the bystander victim of a seemingly gang-related shooting, but as the secrets jude and laila have kept since law school begin to unravel - with the help of a zealous news reporter and the capitol police - aby is forced to consider that jude might not have been an unintended victim of the shooting after all.

meanwhile, as jude receives a bizarre post-shooting diagnosis revealing that his brain is healing in such a way that he can no longer lie, aby worries about her own secret past coming to light. her past is marked by abuse and lies, and even a false accusation that still haunts her. 
unpredictable, unexpected, and startlingly timely, why we lie examines the real life consequences of those who tell the truth and those who lie, and asks the question: is the truth always worth the cost?" read advance praise for why we lie here.

text:
living for others... the past 2 years has taught me the most important lesson of my life. to live for me... being raised as the preachers daughter, i was never taught self expression or that it was even ok to be me. there were strict rules on who i was supposed to be at all times. so when i left the church at 18 i clung to one boyfriend after another who would dictate to me who i was. so desperate for love and affirmation i morphed into whoever they required me to be. i died my hair black for my foreign boyfriend, platinum blonde for the one who liked blondes, wore boots for the guy who wanted boots, red lippy for the guy who wanted red lippy. hell i even tried to be a surfy chic for the surfer dude when i can't even swim. it was so ridiculous and it led to some pretty awful situations. 
it wasn't until one of these over controlling partners nearly killed me that i realized things had to change. i had to start living for me. 
a couple years and countless therapy appointments later i've come out of my shell and out of the closet,  and am living my best life. the last pic is of me now, as is, no filter, i don't know if you can see it but i know the happiness in my eyes and i'm so grateful that i've learnt to live for me. 
#thepreachersdaughter #vikingwoman #vikings #blonde #brunette #blackhair #changes #comingout #churchtoo #metoo #happiness #livingmybestlife #livingforme #livingforothers #selfcare #selfawareness #growingup #glowup #comingout #lesbian #lgbt #femme #femmelesbian

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

text:
i never mentioned this to you...
because i was in shock at the time.
deeply saddened and confused.. ğŸ’”

i spoke to a san diego sorority about sexual assault and anxiety one year ago this week.

i spent dozens of hours preparing for this.
including several visits to the college campus.
donated my time for free, creating a presentation.
hired a photographer to help spread the healing message through social media.

i left the night of the talk overflowing with gratitude, 
cried tears of purpose and joy on my walk out to the parking lot.
felt super connected to the spirit of the universe and my life purpose.

until the next morning.

the sorority sister who had me come speak wrote me an email.
she said she was profoundly upset and disturbed by the content of my talk.
she said she was speaking on behalf of all of the sisters.
that my suggesting mindfulness and deep breathing could alleviate symptoms of anxiety was blatantly untrue.

she said my tips never worked for her ğŸ’”

i was heartbroken.

one third of the ladies raised their hands saying they have panic attacks.
and one of them is telling me something that truly helps is blatantly untrue.

fakkkkkk.

but this is how our nervous system works i thought..
it's biology, not my philosophy, it's the parasympathetic nervous system... it baffled me for awhile, how this could be her truth.

i knew some of the ladies resonated with my talk, i could see their heads nod as i spoke of anxiety and potential solutions.

but worse yet i had my ted talk coming up in a month at another college campus on the same topic.

fakkkk.

i wondered, almost desperately, how can i change my talk so that it didn't offend the people it's intended to help... like still share the truth but in a way that can be heard.. i prayed hard.

then it occurred to me if i stuck with my story 
and not a "5 steps to solve your problem" approach, 
that maybe, just maybe, the people i felt called to help 
could and would 
hear me.

i am so grateful for what i learned that night at the sorority...
my own big lesson in how to be heard, especially with a sensitive topic.

i completely rewrote my ted talk.

text:
woody allen sues amazon studios for terminating movie deal.
_

over a year after the #metoo movement first gained traction in hollywood, it appears as though it has finally caught up with one of the most polarizing figures in the industry. filmmaker woody allen is reportedly suing amazon for breach of contract, alleging that the companyâ€™s studio unit reneged on a four-picture movie deal due to resurfaced sexual abuse allegations. allen is seeking more than $68 million in damages. allen is saying that amazon cannot terminate the contract because they were aware of these allegations before employing him for his services. that, these allegations have already been very well known to amazon and the public. 
_
according to the suit, filed thursday in new york federal court, amazon attempted to terminate its agreements with allen last june.
_

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

this data could then be used to find potential swing voters and create messages tailored to influence them politically.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
this is not really surprising. they've been doing this crime centuries ago. look it up! but this needs to be expose over and over again because these so called 'man of god' is using religion to satisfy their lust.

news bbc news navigation
sections

pope admits clerical abuse of nuns including sexual slavery

pope francis made the admission while visiting the middle east
pope francis has admitted that clerics have sexually abused nuns, and in one case they were kept as sex slaves.

he said in that case his predecessor, pope benedict, was forced to shut down an entire congregation of nuns who were being abused by priests.

it is thought to be the first time that pope francis has acknowledged the sexual abuse of nuns by the clergy.

he said the church was attempting to address the problem but said it was "still going on". last november, the catholic church's global organisation for nuns denounced the "culture of silence and secrecy" that prevented them from speaking out.

the pope's comments come amid long-running cases of sexual abuse of children and young men by priests at the church.

child sex abuse and the catholic church
profile: pope francis
what did pope francis say?
speaking to reporters while on a historic tour of the middle east on tuesday, the pontiff admitted that the church had an issue, and the roots lay in society "seeing women as second class". he said that priests and bishops had abused nuns, but said the church was aware of the "scandal" and was "working on it", adding that a number of clerics had been suspended. "it's a path that we've been on," he said. "pope benedict had the courage to dissolve a female congregation which was at a certain level, because this slavery of women had entered it - slavery, even to the point of sexual slavery - on the part of clerics or the founder." pope francis said sexual abuse of nuns was an ongoing problem, but happened largely in "certain congregations, predominantly new ones". "i think it's still taking place because it's not as though the moment you become aware of something it goes away."

this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
we are young. we can all learn. i had tears in my eyes. i could not leave because i was unwell to leave. i asked you, both of you, all of you, to stop laughing while i was trying to see what i can order because i was not feeling well. you both kept laughing. please. do better. do not hurt us when we are at the lowest point in our lives. our best present to you is our presence. our lives. our smiles. do not laugh when we ask to please stop laughing. please just look away instead of looking me in the eyes and hysterically laughing. i do not want anyone to lose their jobs. i want people to grow and try harder to be patient. please. i beg you. all of me loves all of you. so please, just look away. do not say my name out loud during the dark times. do not tell your coworkers who don't know me about my mistakes that i'm working on. do not give my family another reason to be ashamed of me. i've hurt them enough.

what you see, what i share, is what i allow you to see. this is for me, well, okay, mostly. it's better than driving around the #dtes for an hour to feel better after a senseless #splenda boy calls you crazy and unstable, right? 
then my old car breaks down from overheating, haha. can't make this up, man. i'm just doing my part. my strongest, during the darkest time. i can be your kindest friend, or ...the opposite if you invade my space. no means no. my mind, my rights, my wrists, my body is mine. the world doesn't owe you, me, anyone, anything... but we can all be kinder to each other. let's keep trying. let's keep observing. let's keep growing. #bhavantu #thisisyoga #yoga #discrimination #metoo #instagood glyoubettergetalawyer #and #keepyourdistance #cope #pause #breathe #stretch #your #neck #letsdothisbuddy ğŸ¤œğŸ¤›â¤ğŸ¤¸ğŸ½â€â™€ï¸ #resilient #starbucks #howdareyou #imamazing ğŸ’â€â™‚ï¸ #ionlywishyouaweekofburningpoops #idkwhatelseyet #yourmensbathroomfloorhadpooptrackedinfivedifferentspots #firingwontalwayshelp #wedontneed #toknow #howtoread to #feel #allthefeels

our last step of the #16stepprogram - how boys and men can step up for #metoo.

#repost @mariumjk ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
@safwansubzwari and i paint large scale murals around karachi. sometimes we get hired to paint for cafes or small businesses. this weekend we got hired to paint a mural for #lahootimelo2019, a music and art festival happening in hyderabad. the theme of the festival being 'an ode to the liberated women', we were very excited to work on it. sunday afternoon around 2.30pm we started painting at the festival. we had a lot of men come up to us and talk to us about art and what it means. men came up to take pictures with us. explain to us what this means, how good of a thing this is. children came up to us, to what to paint with us. my husband played some music and a large group of men joined in to have some fun. they were singing and dancing. the vibe overall was extremely positive. we finished the mural and packed up and left for karachi. in the car, i asked my husband what he was thinking about when he was painting. he said he was thinking about painting a mural keeping the theme in mind. but, you see, i was thinking about painting the mural too, but i was also thinking about if the men were taking pictures of me, if my shirt was too short, should i have worn jeans and a t-shirt, are the men coming to close to me, they're staring at me, they're probably definitely staring at me, should i stop and sit down if there are too many of them, what if they say something, what if they just walk by and touch my ass, this was a bad idea, was it a good idea? while thinking all this, i still managed to paint. i guess this is why women are so good at multi-tasking. i think i'm a liberated women. but it's not just the women who need to be liberated, its also the men who need to liberated from the kind of mindset they have and the kind of environment they create. even though nothing happened, the festival had a really good vibe and i'm so glad things like these are happening in pakistan, i really wish there's a time when i don't need to worry about this and i can work as freely as i want to. #feministrant #anodetowomen #metoo #odetowomen #lahootimelo

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
â€œyou are too radicalâ€...
too often i hear that feminists are too aggressive in their language, too excessive in their actions. thus, calling, as i do, historic systematic inequality as â€œwar on womenâ€, rape and sexual harassment as â€œwar crimesâ€and womenâ€™s body oppressed by patriarchal institutions and industries as â€œbattlefieldâ€ is often seen by those critics as excessive comparisons. among those critics, unfortunately, are often women and even feminists themselves. unnecessary tolerance towards the status quo or fear of being radical, leads some to go against their allies. weâ€™ve seen such opposition at every womenâ€™s uprising, every time women were about to bring progress. during the #metoo campaign, such opposition was represented by a 100 of women, academics, business professionals and celebrities, who published a tribune pour une Â«libertÃ©dâ€™importunerÂ»in the french magazine le monde. in this tribune, the women accused #metoo campaign of â€œgoing too farâ€and â€œgoing backwardsâ€at the same time. already habitually, feminist revolt was once again proclaimed to be a manifestation â€œof the hate towards menâ€. while appreciating diversity of opinions, tactics and language used by feminists, i tend to defend the necessity of the words used above as well as radical statements of fellow women. speaking out against systematic violence against women isn't hate of men, but rather this very violence is a manifestation of the historic hate towards women in the male world. rape, sexual harassment and other forms of violence committed against womenâ€™s bodies are the crimes, and not signs of passion or attraction towards women. letâ€™s finally start seeing things as they are, and not as we were told to see them. my radicalism in calling sexism â€œwar on womenâ€and rape as â€œwar crimeâ€isn't optional, it is necessary if we are to move forward. excess was often a way to progress. well behaved girls never made history, as it is known. and it is surely only by going too far, by crossing the borders, women could obtained their fundamental rights, like the right to vote or contraception. 
what do you think?

text:
#metoo movement has created a fear in men that if they do anything wrong to a girl she will go out and speak, says a hopeful neena gupta.
shedding light on an unseen shift in bollywood, neena says, â€œa major change happened in last one year, today there are powerful roles written for girls, girls are directing the film, they are going out and earning for themselves. even for men, you donâ€™t have to be a very good-looking guy to get main or important parts. you can be a boy-next-door and become a hero.
talking about the metoo movement which started in bollywood and rajkumar hiraniâ€™s name being dragged in it, she said, â€œit is very difficult to prove sometimes. more often than, it is an old thing and after 10 or 15 years it gets very difficult to prove. also, these things happen in private so there is no witness. you have to take the word. somebody could be lying, it's difficult to gauge. but i feel because of this movement, a person will think 100 times before doing something. "there are lots of people who will take advantage of this movement, which is obvious, but one good thing is that this movement has created a fear in men that if they do anything wrong to a girl, she will raise her voice, instead of staying mum."
recalling the days she faced all this harassment, neena narrates, â€œi lost lots of work because of this, but once i gathered the courage and spoke about it. i was very new and somebody told me a very bad thing which i couldnâ€™t tolerate. i was disgusted, he told me such dirty things in front of everyone because i was not giving it. i was very angry and i spoke about it in some of the magazines. it did not deter him, he again spoke badly about me. he was very powerful and i was nothing as i was very new, we continued fighting and it became very dirty. my friends advised me to stop. they told me that nobody will believe me, he is not getting affected, i will lose my respect because i was a nobody, so after that i said nothing. afterwards, whenever something like this used to happen, i would leave the project, never go back on sets and dealt with it quietly.â€
.
.
#metoo #metoomovement #neenagupta #masabagupta #bollywood #badhaiho #india #films #movies

text:
have you ever been hurt so bad that your whole body is crying , your heart is aching so much , you cant take a breath ...you can not say a word or move ..your mind is concentrated only on your pain while heavy tears streaming down your cheecks and suicide thoughts come to your mind ??
once the  ambulance was not called even if i did not breath for a panic attack ...better to keep the silence and hide the fact 
words hurt more than actions 
and i have never known the real  reason for that ...no apologies , no a single sorry  from his mouth in all these years ..he will never apology for his words and i am not  here to await for his excuses 
but i have won ..because my dreams  are still  here , in my mind  working for a better life far from his  pathetic circus full of white masks of perverted clowns
@darkmoonlifemodel

text:
science and gender equality are both vital for the achievement of the internationally agreed development goals, including the 2030 agenda for sustainable development. over the past 15 years, the global community has made a lot of effort in inspiring and engaging women and girls in science. yet women and girls continue to be excluded from participating fully in science. 
at present, less than 30 per cent of researchers worldwide are women. according to unesco data (2014 - 2016), only around 30 per cent of all female students select stem-related fields in higher education. globally, female studentsâ€™ enrolment is particularly low in ict (3 per cent), natural science, mathematics and statistics (5 per cent) and in engineering, manufacturing and construction (8 per cent). long-standing biases and gender stereotypes are steering girls and women away from science related fields. as in the real world, the world on screen reflects similar biasesâ€”the 2015 gender bias without borders study by the geena davis institute showed that of the onscreen characters with an identifiable stem job, only 12 per cent were women. .
.
